 perspective of its survivors. Based on in-depth interviews conducted over the course of fifteen years, the authors take a holistic approach by tracing how victims experienced the horrific events, as well as how they have coped with the aftermath as they struggled to resume their lives. The Rwanda genocide deserves study and documentation not only because of the failure of the Western world to intervene, but also because it raises profound questions about the ways survivors create a new life out of the ashes of all that was destroyed. How do they deal with the all-encompassing traumas of genocide? Is forgiveness possible? And what does the process of rebuilding teach us about genocide, trauma, and human life?  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aChildren and genocidezRwandaxHistoryy20th century. 0aGenocide survivorszRwandaxPsychological aspects. 0aGenocide survivorszRwandaxPsychology. 0aTutsi (African people)xCrimes againstzRwandaxPsychological aspects. 0aWidowszRwandaxHistoryy20th century. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh  aalienation.  aanthropology.  abodies.  achildren.  adeath.  aethnic cleansing.  aethnicity.  aforgiveness.  agendered violence.  agenocide.  agrief.  aguilt.  ahealing.  ahuman life.  ahutu.  aidentity.  ainterviews.  aisolation.  ajustice.  amass killing.  amental health.  anonfiction.  aoral history.  aorphans.  apolitical science.  aptsd.  arace.  aracism.  arape.  arebuilding.  areconciliation.  arwanda.  asexual violence.  asocial science.  astate violence.  asurvivors.  atrauma.  atutsi.  aviolence.  awar crimes.  awomen.1 aMeyerowitz, Beth E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNg, Lauren C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/r